namque alid ex alio clarescet nec tibi caeca 1115 nox iter eripiet quin ultima naturai pervideas: ita res accendent lumina rebus.

1105 penetralia Nico. for tonetralia3 rightly followed by all the old eds. before Lamb. who reads tonitralia: V1 865 sonitus all mss. for penitus: neither tone- tralia nor tonitralia is Latin. 1108 abeat Ed. after Mar. Junt. for abeant wrongly adapted to the adjacent plural: comp. v1 286: omnis agrees with tem-a: comp. VI 605 sqq. ε Lach. in 1106 reads omnia, as also 11 719 without authority. 1114 sei Ed. after Nico. Flor. 31 Camb. Mon. etc. for sic: a verse is here lost whjch I feel sure was of this kind, Cetera iam poteris per te tute ipse videre, with which the preceding words parva perductus opella must be joined: Lucr. says it is hard to master his principles, but when that is thoroughly done, then led on with little trouble you may learn the rest yourself : comp. especially 400—417, and see Gamb. Journ. of phil. 1 p. 374. Lach. for sic reads scio and perdoctus for perductus, and then gets no satisfactory sense: Mar. and Junt. read ηοη for nec in 1115: Lamb. perfunctus for perdoctus: Bern. sis, and perdoctus after Lach.
